.TH MKNOD "1" "April 2026" "GNU coreutils 9.11" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
mknod \- make block or character special files
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B mknod
[\fI\,OPTION\/\fR]... \fI\,NAME TYPE \/\fR[\fI\,MAJOR MINOR\/\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.\" Add any additional description here
.PP
Create the special file NAME of the given TYPE.
.PP
Mandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.
.TP
\X'tty: link https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/coreutils.html#mknod-m'\fB\-m, \-\-mode=\,MODE\fP\X'tty: link'\/\fR
set file permission bits to MODE, not a=rw \- umask
.TP
\X'tty: link https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/coreutils.html#mknod-Z'\fB\-Z\fP\X'tty: link'
set the SELinux security context to default type
.TP
\X'tty: link https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/coreutils.html#mknod--context'\fB\-\-context[=CTX]\fP\X'tty: link'
like \fB\-Z\fR, or if CTX is specified then set the
SELinux or SMACK security context to CTX
.TP
\X'tty: link https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/mknod#mknod--help'\fB\-\-help\fP\X'tty: link'
display this help and exit
.TP
\X'tty: link https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/mknod#mknod--version'\fB\-\-version\fP\X'tty: link'
output version information and exit
.PP
Both MAJOR and MINOR must be specified when TYPE is b, c, or u, and they
must be omitted when TYPE is p.  If MAJOR or MINOR begins with 0x or 0X,
it is interpreted as hexadecimal; otherwise, if it begins with 0, as octal;
otherwise, as decimal.  TYPE may be:
.TP
b
create a block (buffered) special file
.TP
c, u
create a character (unbuffered) special file
.TP
p
create a FIFO
.PP
Your shell may have its own version of mknod, which usually supersedes
the version described here.  Please refer to your shell's documentation
for details about the options it supports.
